Preamble:
The Unified Free and Open (UFOL) license is a comprehensive legal instrument governing to use, modification, and distribution of software. The primary aim is to facilitate an open and collaborative environment, ensuring the rights and responsibilities of all parties involved. By using, modifying, or distributing software under this license, you agree to abide by its terms and conditions.

Definitions:
Software: Refers to the computer program or programs covered by this license.

Derivative Works: Encompasses modifications, extensions, adaptations, or any other form of alteration made to the original software.

Principles and Rules:
Grant of License:

Subject to the terms and conditions of this license, users are granted a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive license to use, modify, and distribute the software.

Distribution Requirements:

Any distribution of the software must include:
The original copyright notice.
A copy of this license.
Clear documentation of any modifications made.

Distribution Terms:

Anyone has the right to redistribute the Software as long as any form of malicious code is not injected and the Distribution does not violate the law.

Derivative Works Obligation:

Derivative works must be identified as such, and they must be distributed under the same UFO license.

Attribution and Credits:

Proper attribution to the original authors and contributors must be maintained in all copies, derivative works, and distributions of the software.
Compatibility with Other Software:

Derivative works that are distributed or combined with other software must be compatible with the terms of the licenses of those other software components.

Laws and Jurisdiction
Governing Law:

This license is governed by principles of international law, including widely recognized treaties, conventions, and agreements that promote global standards in software licensing and intellectual property rights. These include, but are not limited to, the Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works and the United Nations Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods (CISG). In cases where international law does not provide a resolution, the laws of the governing country or the US shall apply as a secondary governing framework.
Venue:

Any legal action or proceeding arising under this license shall be resolved through internationally recognized arbitration bodies, such as the International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) or the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL), unless otherwise specified by the parties involved. Where arbitration is not feasible, proceedings shall be brought in the courts of the governing country.

Trademark Protection
Trademark Use:

The license does not grant any rights to use the names, trademarks, or service marks of the licensor, except as required for reasonable and customary use in describing the origin of the software.

